    <description>
        <div>
            <p>The Foreign Service Act of 1924 (May 24, 1924; 43 Stat. 146) abolished numerical
                titles for Assistant Secretaries of State while authorizing the appointment of a
                fourth Assistant Secretary. Between 1924 and 1944, one Assistant Secretary was in
                charge of administration, budgets, and finance. Duties of the others varied with
                each appointment, including at various times legal affairs, consular affairs,
                economic affairs, and Inter-American affairs. On Dec 8, 1944, an Act of Congress (58
                Stat. 798) increased the number of Assistant Secretaries to six. Ever since the
                Department’s reorganization of Dec 20, 1944, Assistant Secretaries of State have
                received functional or geographic designations. Unless otherwise specified, they
                have been commissioned as “an Assistant Secretary of State.”</p>
        </div>
    </description>
